\f2 Today is the anniversary of 
\f3\b\fs28 \cf2 \cb3 \expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
August Ferdinand M\'f6bius
\f2\b0  (1790-1868) ,{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Germany"}}{\fldrslt \cf4 German}} {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mathematician"}}{\fldrslt \cf4 mathematician}} and theoretical {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Astronomer"}}{\fldrslt \cf4 astronomer}}.\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf2 He is best known for his discovery of the {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/M%C3%B6bius_strip"}}{\fldrslt \cf4 M\'f6bius strip}}, a {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Non-orientable"}}{\fldrslt \cf4 non-orientable}} two-dimensional surface with only one side when {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Embedding"}}{\fldrslt \cf4 embedded}} in three-dimensional {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Euclidean_space"}}{\fldrslt \cf4 Euclidean space}}. M\'f6bius was the first to introduce {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Homogeneous_coordinates"}}{\fldrslt \cf4 homogeneous coordinates}} into {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Projective_geometry"}}{\fldrslt \cf4 projective geometry}}. He is recognized for the introduction of the {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Barycentric_coordinate_system"}}{\fldrslt \cf4 Barycentric coordinate system}}.\cb1 \
\cb3 Many mathematical concepts are named after him, including the {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/M%C3%B6bius_plane"}}{\fldrslt \cf4 M\'f6bius plane}}, the {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/M%C3%B6bius_transformation"}}{\fldrslt \cf4 M\'f6bius transformations}}, important in projective geometry, and the {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/M%C3%B6bius_transform"}}{\fldrslt \cf4 M\'f6bius transform}} of number theory. His interest in {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Number_theory"}}{\fldrslt \cf4 number theory}} led to the important {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/M%C3%B6bius_function"}}{\fldrslt \cf4 M\'f6bius function}} \uc0\u956 (
\f4\i n
\f2\i0 ) and the {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/M%C3%B6bius_inversion_formula"}}{\fldrslt \cf4 M\'f6bius inversion formula}}. In Euclidean geometry, he systematically developed the use of signed angles and line segments as a way of simplifying and unifying results.
